If the Original Author exercises this right, the additional permissions shall apply to the Program going forward. Contributors agree that such additional permissions may be granted for their Contributions, and no further consent from Contributors is required. This provision is intended to give the Original Author the flexibility to make the Program more open as the Project evolves. The Original Author may not, under any circumstances, impose additional restrictions beyond those already present in this License, nor may they revoke the rights granted under this License.

Any commercial licenses granted prior to such additional permissions remain valid and are not superseded by this Section. Licensees holding commercial licenses may choose to operate under either the commercial license terms or the additional permissions, at their option.

13. Automatic Transition to AGPL Upon Abandonment

If the Original Author ([AUTHOR]) has not:

· Released a new version of the Program (including any minor or major update), and
· Responded to any licensing inquiry or other communication directed to the contact information provided in the repository, and
· Made a public statement regarding the ongoing maintenance or licensing of the Program,

for a continuous period of five (5) years, then upon the expiration of such five-year period, this License shall automatically terminate with respect to the Program, and the Program shall thereafter be governed by the terms of the GNU Affero General Public License v3.0 (AGPL-3.0) or any later version, as published by the Free Software Foundation.

This transition applies to all copies of the Program, including all Contributions, and is intended to ensure that the Program does not become orphaned or abandoned under a restrictive license. Upon this transition, all rights and obligations under this License cease, and the terms of the AGPL-3.0 apply exclusively.

Exception for Existing Commercial Licenses: Any commercial licenses or additional permissions granted by the Original Author ([AUTHOR]) under Section 12 prior to the transition shall remain in full force and effect. Recipients of such licenses retain the rights granted to them under those separate agreements, regardless of the transition to AGPL. The AGPL transition applies only to users who were operating under this License, not to licensees who obtained separate commercial permissions.

The Original Author may prevent this transition at any time before it occurs by:

· Releasing a new version of the Program,
· Responding to any pending inquiry, or
· Making a public statement in the repository indicating that the Program remains under active maintenance.

14. Artificial Intelligence Training Restriction

Notwithstanding any other provision of this License, you may not use the Program, in whole or in part, for the purpose of training, fine-tuning, or otherwise improving the parameters of any machine learning or artificial intelligence model without prior written permission of the Original Author ([AUTHOR]).

Prohibited uses include:

* Using the Program as training or fine-tuning data for any AI/ML model.
* Using the Program for representation learning, embedding model training, or similar processes that modify model weights.
* Using the Program to create or enhance datasets specifically intended for model training.

For clarity, the following uses are explicitly permitted:

* Running, executing, or deploying the Program.
* Indexing, searching, caching, or otherwise storing the Program for retrieval purposes.
* Static analysis, security scanning, or code review (including automated tools).
* Evaluation or benchmarking of AI systems, provided no model training or parameter updates occur.
* Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) and similar systems where the Program is used as external reference material and not used to train model weights.

The Original Author ([AUTHOR]) may grant written exceptions to this restriction at their sole discretion.

Any violation of this Section constitutes a material breach and results in termination under Section 11.

